<DOC><DOCNO> AP880524-0098 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0913EDT</FILEID><FIRST>d a PM-BRF--MobTrial     05-24 0166</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Mob Trial,0169</SECOND><HEAD>Reputed Mob Captain Sentenced to 10 Years</HEAD><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A man prosecutors say was a SouthernCalifornia crime family leader has been sentenced to 10 years inprison on drug and conspiracy charges.   Luigi Gelfuso Jr., 62, pleaded guilty last month to one counteach of conspiracy to distribute cocaine, conspiracy to useextortion to collect a gambling debt and conspiracy to violatelabor laws by taking money to guarantee a movie was made withnon-union workers.   His sentencing came Monday, a week after his reputed boss, PeterJohn Milano, received a six-year sentence. The two were among 15people indicted last year on extortion, racketeering and drugtrafficking charges.   When the indictment was announced, U.S. Attorney Robert C.Bonner said, ``The main body of La Cosa Nostra in Los Angeles hasbeen severely gutted.''   Seven of those indicted were sentenced last week, includingMilano, under a plea bargain. Sentences ranged from 10 years inprison to five years' probation.</TEXT></DOC>